{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17528642","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17528642"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:45:25+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:45:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14320"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14320","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14320"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.18,0.02,0.02,0.07,0.72]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7015"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54666"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7015","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7015"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14320"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40193"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"20"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"393"},{"type":"tags","id":"1115"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"16679"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30672"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44560"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44803"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54666","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/54666"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 55-year-old man presents to the surgical oncology clinic following referral from his General Practice clinic for a 2 cm sized biopsy-proven malignant melanoma over his right shin. He is otherwise asymptomatic. The excisional biopsy result performed by his GP showed a malignant melanoma with Breslow thickness of 1.5 mm, no ulcerations, mitotic rate 0.8, and no lymphovascular invasion. He has no personal or family history of skin cancers. He has no other medical or surgical history and does not take any regular medications. He smokes 10 cigarettes a day and does not drink alcohol. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, there is an excisional biopsy scar over the right shin with no residual melanoma seen and no clinically pathological right inguinal nodes. He has been advised to proceed with a wide local excision of the excisional biopsy scar with 1 cm margin.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is another critical investigation to assist in the management of this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["CT chest, abdomen and pelvis","MRI head","LDH","Ultrasound right inguinal nodes","Sentinel lymph node biopsy"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESentinel lymph node biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E (SLNB) is the most appropriate next investigation for this patient. SLNB is recommended for melanomas with a Breslow thickness greater than 1 mm, as in this case (1.5 mm). It is a minimally invasive procedure that identifies and removes the first draining lymph node(s) from the primary melanoma site for histological examination. The sentinel lymph node status is the most important prognostic factor for melanoma and guides further management decisions, including the need for completion lymphadenectomy or adjuvant therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT chest, abdomen and pelvis\u003C/strong\u003E is not routinely recommended for patients with localized melanoma (stages I and II) unless there are specific signs or symptoms suggesting metastatic disease. In this case, the patient is asymptomatic, and there is no evidence of advanced disease based on the information provided.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMRI head\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated as a routine investigation for melanoma unless there are neurological symptoms or signs suggesting brain metastases. This patient has no such symptoms, and brain imaging is not typically performed for early-stage melanoma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELDH\u003C/strong\u003E (lactate dehydrogenase) is a serum biomarker that can be elevated in metastatic melanoma. However, it is not routinely measured in early-stage melanoma and has limited utility in this setting. LDH is more commonly used for monitoring patients with known metastatic disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUltrasound right inguinal nodes\u003C/strong\u003E, while potentially useful, is less sensitive and specific than SLNB for detecting micrometastases. Ultrasound is typically reserved for follow-up of patients with melanoma or for those who cannot undergo SLNB. Clinical examination did not reveal any palpable lymphadenopathy, further reducing the utility of ultrasound in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, SLNB is the most appropriate next step for this patient with a 1.5 mm thick melanoma. It provides crucial prognostic information and helps guide further management decisions. The results of SLNB, along with other factors such as Breslow thickness, ulceration status, and mitotic rate, will be used to determine the final stage of the melanoma and inform decisions about adjuvant therapy and follow-up protocols. The planned wide local excision with a 1 cm margin is appropriate for a melanoma of this thickness and should be performed in conjunction with the SLNB.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Sentinel lymph node biopsy is recommended for melanomas with a Breslow thickness \u003E1mm or other high-risk features.","Sentinel lymph node status is the most important prognostic factor for melanoma and guides further management.","Wide local excision with appropriate margins is the standard treatment for primary cutaneous melanoma."],"references":["Br\u0103ni\u015fteanu DE, Cozmin M, Porumb-Andrese E, Br\u0103ni\u015fteanu D, Toader MP, Iosep D, Sinigur D, Br\u0103ni\u015fteanu CI, Br\u0103ni\u015fteanu G, Porumb V, P\u00eenzariu AC, B\u0103il\u0103 SL, Nicolescu AC. Sentinel Lymph Node Biopsy in Cutaneous Melanoma, a Clinical Point of View. Medicina (Kaunas). 2022 Nov 3;58(11):1589. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC9698247/","Thompson JF; Cancer Council Australia. Australian Cancer Network. New Zealand, Ministry of Health. Clinical Practice Guidelines for the Management of Melanoma in Australia and New Zealand. Cancer Council Australia; Sydney, Australia: 2008. Available at: https://melanomapatients.org.au/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/cp111.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40193"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14320"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40193","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/40193"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-09T10:05:40+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-09T10:08:13+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7015"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54666"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"upda